%%TITLE
Prognostic impact of human papillomavirus status, survivin, and epidermal growth factor receptor expression on survival in patients treated with radiochemotherapy for very advanced nonresectable oropharyngeal cancer.
%%ABSTRACT
The influence of human papillomavirus (HPV) status on survival for patients with very advanced inoperable oropharyngeal SCC treated with radiochemotherapy (RCT) was studied.Patients received either 69.2 Gy with concomitant boost (ccb) or 70 Gy conventionally fractionated (cf), weekly paclitaxel 40 mg/m(2), and carboplatin area under the concentration-time curve (AUC) 1. Tumor was analyzed for the presence of high-risk HPV-DNA using polymerase chain reaction (PCR) and direct DNA sequencing. p16-expression, survivin, and epidermal growth factor receptor (EGFR) expression were evaluated by immunohistochemistry and influence on survival was calculated.Of 52 patients, 25.0% were HPV positive and 75.0% HPV negative. The 2-year progression-free survival (PFS) was 70.1% for p16-positive patients and 37.1% for p16-negative patients (p = .005). The 3-year overall survival (OS) rate was 43.9% for all patients and did not significantly differ between the groups. Neither survivin nor EGFR expression influenced PFS or OS significantly.HPV status influences PFS in patients with advanced, nonresectable tumor stages but not OS. Additional risk factors seem to have a stronger influence on survival than HPV status.
%%PATIENTS AND METHODS
Patient population and treatment protocol
Patients with advanced, nonresectable squamous cell carcinomas of the oropharynx treated with concurrent radiochemotherapy at the Cologne University Hospital from 2000 to 2008 were included. In accord with local standard operating procedure, the therapy of all newly diagnosed patients with tumors, presenting with advanced HNSCC, is discussed in an interdisciplinary tumor board (consisting of experienced head and neck surgeons, radia- tion oncologists, and medical oncologists). Staging inves- tigations include MRI or CT scans of the neck, thoracic CT scan, full blood cell count, serum chemistry profile, electrocardiogram (ECG), complete history and physical examination, and assessment of Karnofsky performance status. Details of a standardized diagnostic approach and of the criteria for nonresectable tumors were reported pre- viously.20 If tumors were considered nonresectable, con- current radiochemotherapy was recommended after exclu- sion of contraindications to a combined modality treatment. Radiochemotherapy protocol has been previ- ously described in detail.21
Patient characteristics. Fifty-two patients treated in accord with this protocol were included in this analysis. Forty- two patients were male (80.8%) and 10 female (19.2%). Median age was 56.3 years (range, 34–76 years). All patients had oropharyngeal SCCs. Detailed patient char- acteristics are given in Table 1.
Radiotherapy. The following radiotherapy protocols were used.
Hyperfractionated-accelerated radiotherapy with con- comitant boost (ccb) to total dose of 69.2 Gy. Primary tu- mor region and bilateral cervical and supraclavicular lymph nodes (PTV2) received 2 Gy once daily, to a total dose of 50.0 Gy. Additionally, macroscopically involved primary tumor and lymph nodes (PTV1) were treated

Conventional fractionation (cf). PTV2 received 1.8 Gy once daily, up to 50.4 Gy. PTV1 was treated with the same fraction size to a total dose of 70 to 72 Gy. Total treatment time was 40 days. PTV1 included macroscopi- cally involved primary tumor and lymph nodes, visible on initial diagnostic CT scan or MRI. PTV2 additionally included potentially microscopically involved lymph node areas, depending on primary tumor location.22
Three-dimensional conformal radiotherapy planning was performed. A typical plan for PTV2 included 6 to 9 fields and 3 to 6 fields for PTV1. Maximal tolerated spi- nal cord dose was kept below 50 Gy (V50 1%). In the early study phase a conventional treatment plan using opposing fields and electron beams for dorsocervical lymph nodes was used to treat PTV2. Linear accelerators were used delivering 6 to 15 MeV photons and 4 to 15 MeV electrons. Radiotherapy was given within 1 hour after chemotherapy.
Chemotherapy. Concurrent chemotherapy was administered once weekly during radiotherapy with antiemetic cover- age and consisted of carboplatin AUC1 and paclitaxel 40 mg/m2. A maximum of 6 intravenous chemotherapy cycles were given. Paclitaxel was started after carboplatin and antiallergic premedication was given (intravenous administration of antihistaminics and dexamethasone). The total infusion time was 3 hours. Dose reduction or
discontinuation of chemotherapy was performed if any hematologic grade 4 toxicity occurred. A full blood count and basic clinical chemistry was done once a week or more frequently if clinically indicated. Additional antie- metics (5HT3-antagonists, corticosteroids, and metoclo- pramide) were used if clinically indicated.
Determination of HPV status and other prognostic markers
Studies of human tissue biopsies were performed in accord with the requirements of the local research ethics committee. Tumor specimens of all cases were frozen in liquid nitrogen and stored at 800C. In addition, tissue was fixed in 4% buffered formalin and embedded in par-
affin by routine procedures at the Department of Pathol- ogy of the University of Cologne. Slides from all blocks were reviewed by a single pathologist to select represen- tative areas of the carcinoma for immunohistochemistry. The criteria for block selection were vital tumor tissue without necrosis and a front of invasion. Only blocks with estimates of at least 70% tumor cells were included.
Sample preparation, polymerase chain reaction, and HPV typing. Tissues were processed as previously described.8 After confirming the integrity of DNA by b-globing gene PCR,
41 HPV sequences were detected by highly sensitive nested PCR protocols with degenerated primers A10/ A5–A6/A8 for HPV group A (genital/mucosal) HPVs and CP62/70–CP65/69a for group B1 (cutaneous/EV) HPVs PCR products (10 l) were separated in 2% agarose gels and visualized by ethidium bromide staining. HPV typing was performed as described previously.8
Immunohistochemical staining. The following primary anti- bodies were used: monoclonal mouse anti-human p16INK4A antibody (Roche MTM Laboratories, Westbor- ough, MA); polyclonal rabbit anti-human survivin anti- body (Novus Biologicals Inc., Littleton, CO), and mono- clonal mouse anti-human EGFR antibody, clone 31G7 (Zytomed, Berlin, Germany).
Immunohistochemical staining was performed on 5-lm- thick formaldehyde-fixed, paraffin-embedded tissue sec- tions as previously described.5,14 Primary antibodies were detected using the avidin-biotinylated peroxidase complex (ABC) procedure (Chem Mate Detection kit; Dako Cyto- mation, Carpinteria, CA). Peroxidase activity was visual- ized using 3-Amino-9-Ethylcarbazol (AEC, Dako Cytoma- tion) and sections were counterstained with hematoxylin. Each analysis included negative and positive controls.
Strong nuclear staining and strong cytoplasmic staining were considered positive for p16 expression. p16 immu- nostaining was regarded as overexpression if it was strong and diffuse and more than 60% of the tumor cells were p16-positive. Biopsy sample was classified as HPV-asso- ciated if it showed p16 overexpression and detectable high-risk HPV DNA.
Cytoplasmic survivin staining levels were determined in accord with Lo Muzio23: a mean percentage of cyto- plasmic-positive tumor cells was determined by examin- ing 300 cells in 4 areas at 400 magnification. The tumors were assigned to 1 of the following categories:
score 0, <5%; score 1, 5% to 25%; score 2, 26% to 50%;
score 3, 51% to 75%; score 4, >75%. Slides were consid- ered nuclear positive when more than 5% of all tumor
cell nuclei were stained regardless of the cytoplasmic staining levels.
The EGFR slides were classified to scores 0 to 3 as fol- lows: score 0 was considered when <10% of all tumor cells were stained; score 1 was considered in cases of faint or barely perceptible membrane staining in >10% of all tumor cells and in cases of heterogeneous staining,
weak partial, and/or complete membrane staining was shown in >50% of stained cells; score 2 was considered when moderate membrane staining was shown in >10% of tumor cells and in cases of heterogeneous staining,
moderate partial, and/or complete membrane staining shown in >50% of stained tumor cells; score 3 was con- sidered in cases of strong membrane staining in >10% of all tumor cells and in cases of heterogeneous staining,
strong partial, and/or complete membrane staining shown in >50% of all tumor cells.
Toxicity assessment and follow-up
Acute treatment toxicity was evaluated daily during chemotherapy, weekly during radiotherapy, and docu- mented using the World Health Organization (WHO) cri- teria. If clinically indicated, toxicity was monitored more often. Late toxicity was monitored at every follow-up visit using the Common Toxicity Criteria (CTC) v.3 and the LENT-SOMA scale. First, follow-up was done 6 weeks after completion of the treatment, continuing in 3- month intervals for 1 year followed by 6-month intervals until disease progression or death. Assessment was per- formed by both a head and neck surgeon and a radiation oncologist and included physical examination and history and CT scan or MRI scan of the neck. Suspected recur- rent disease was confirmed by pathohistological examina- tion if feasible.
Statistics
Survival data were estimated in accord with the Kaplan–Meier method. Overall survival (OS) was defined as the interval from the first day of treatment to either time of death or last time of follow-up alive. Progression- free survival (PFS) was calculated from the first day of treatment to either death or diagnosis of recurrent disease (local or distant metastases) or last follow-up alive. Survi- vin, p16, and HPV status were analyzed using cross-tabu- lations and chi-square test. Results were considered sig-
nificant if the 2-sided value of p < .05. Univariate analyses were done using log-rank testing. Calculations
and data management were done using SPSS statistics
17.0 (SPSS Inc., Chicago, IL).
